rt to take advantage of it in the first release of Star).I should think that smooth scrolling will be much simpler for Laurel becauseyour window is full width and you have the features of the Alto displaycontroller.  I believe that the strategy is something along the following lines:	Maintain a bitmap somewhat larger than the window being scrolled (25%	is the number that comes to mind).  This bitmap can be in two parts, one	part being the bitmap for the window itself, and the other part being an	"extension" which is allocated at the time the scrolling starts.  Treat this	combined bitmap as a circular buffer for lines being displayed.	Have two processes, a producer and a consumer.  The producer paints new	lines into the undisplayed portion of the bitmap.  The consumer wakes up	on every vertical retrace, checks a counter or clock, and (if it is time)	trims one line off the top of the displayed portion and adds one line to the	bottom.  This trimming is done by adjusting the pointers and counts in	the DCB's for the two parts of the bitmap.  The line at the top is returned	to the producer; if the line at the bottom is not ready, scrolling takes a	hiccup and waits.	When the user stops scrolling, you need to consolidate all of the displayed	lines into your primary bitmap and throw away the extension.If you are able to do this or something equivalent within the limitations ofLaurel, I think you will have a lot of friends./Hugh*start*00665 00024 US Date: 9 Jan. 1981 3:14 pm PST (Friday)From: Schroeder.PASubject: AltoDir's idea of legal filenamesTo: Brotz---------------------------Date: 9 Jan. 1981 2:18 pm PST (Friday)From: Newman.ESSubject: AltoDir's idea of legal filenames...To: LaurelSupport.paReply-To: Newmancc: Newman...doesn't quite match that of the Alto Operating system. For instance, it allowedme to rename a file to the new name "@#", but could not delete that file once itwas created. The Executive and Neptune couldn't d