r.Any other mouse activity, or DEL, simply cancels the prompt, disables editing inthe brackets, and does what the mouse would do in that instance.  Now it's lessmodeful.Yellow could continue to mean Blue for a while, only after Red though, just toallow people to change their ways.No suggestion about the secondary confirmation requests when zapping old filesor tossing out undelivered messages -- current scheme's as good as any?You may recognize this as a meander back towards the command/bracketsemantics of BravoX, which I like.  The new thing would be Red as an easierway to edit the whole bracket field than BravoX provides.  If you also allowedselection and editing within brackets, you'd just about have a superset of theBravoX semantics again, except that the referent of ESC would sometimes beambiguous.Side point:  what prompted me to think about this again was some combination ofplaying with the new scrolling stuff, and my discovery that for somebracket-parameter commands (e.g., Get, Put), ESC is the ONLY valid confirmationcharacter, whereas for others, either ESC or Yellow will do.  That reminded me ofthe more general simplification, which would among other things cure theproblem with Get, and ...*start*00623 00024 US Date: 8 Feb. 1981 3:11 pm PST (Sunday)From: Schroeder.PASubject: "Files" nits / wishesTo: Brotz---------------------------Date: 6 Feb. 1981 6:06 pm PST (Friday)From: Hamilton.ESSubject: "Files" nits / wishesTo: LaurelSupport.PAcc: Hamilton(1) It seems a little strange that, to ctrl-del out of deleting a series of files, youhave to type a <CR> in addition to the ctrl-del, when it's sitting there asking forconfirmation.(2) It sure would be nice to have a "confirm all deletes automatically" feature ala IFS.--Bruce------------------------------------------------------------*start*00569 00024 US Date: 10 Feb. 1981 3:26 pm PST (Tuesday)From: schmidt.PASubject: MType under Laurel 6To: Lyon, BaskettRepl