rs for this purpose.-Control+Space will advance the caret over the next character (logicallyequivalent to Shift+BS followed by re-typing the character).-Com+Space will advance the caret over the next word.-Shift added to either of the above will reverse the direction.[I have no very strong opinion on which should be the default direction.]Date: 29 Oct. 1980 6:20 pm PST (Wednesday)From: HorningSubject: The Disk, The Clock, and DELAs I was watching my disk pages tick down one by one, and the displayed timeon the "clock" get farther and farther behind, I had leisure for the followingseries of thoughts:1) Why is it any easier to update the free disk page count than the clock?[Actually, I presume that it isn't, it's just another routine's responsibility.]2) Why couldn't the page count update routine also call the clock updateroutine?[After all, the cost of the update must be small compared to allocating or freeinga disk page.]3) Why couldn't this same routine also check for DEL-for-cancel?[Most of the things I would like to cancel use up disk space--slowly butinexorably.  Further, anything that uses the disk must ALREADY be prepared tocope with involuntary cancellation.]*start*00668 00024 US Date: 24 Feb. 1981 12:38 pm PST (Tuesday)From: Horning.PASubject: Name CompletionTo: Brotzcc: LaurelImp^Doug,Now that you have code to scan the file cache and directory for names matchingrestricted patterns, how about doing so whenever the name in brackets doesn'tmatch any existing file name?  If the contents of the brackets is a prefix of asingle file, then extend the contents to the full name, otherwise don't (much likethe existing Alto Executive convention).This would make long, meaningful names less burdensome, and help to alleviatethe problem of remembering what abbreviation has been chosen for a file name.Jim H.*start*01470 00024 US Date: 26 Feb. 1981 1:30 pm PST (Thursday)From: Levin.PASubject: Flexible mail stampsTo: Karltoncc: Schroeder, Brotz, LevinIt appears that variable-sized stamps work in Laurel 6T31.  To permit gracefulfuture expansion, we would like to have some conventions for the format of thevariable part.  In particular, it should be a sequence of self-identifying entities,thereby allowing multiple independent programs to manipulate it.  I propose thefollowing format:Following the fixed part of the stamp (i.e., the initial 24 characters ending in aCR), there is an optional variable part, which is present iff the second decimalnumber in the fixed part exceeds 24.  The syntax of the variable part is asfollows:variable-part ::= @ item-list @item-list ::= <empty> | item-list itemitem ::= byte-length space type space contentsbyte-length ::= <5-character decimal number as in the fixed part>type ::= <5-character decimal number as in the fixed part>contents ::= <sequence of byte-length minus 4 characters>space ::= <040C>Semantics:Types are assigned by a central authority (LaurelSupport).  The byte-length isthe total length of the item in bytes, including the 12 characters occupied by thebyte-count, type, and associate spaces.  Thus, a count of < 12 is illegal.  Theserules imply that the second count in the fixed part of the header can onlylegally assume the values 24, 26 (variable part is "@@"), and >= 38.Roy*start*00376 00024 US Date: 3 March 1981 11:47 am PST (Tuesday)From: Levin.PASubject: Small correction to Flexible mail stamps semanticsTo: Karlton, BrotzReply-To: Levincc: Schroeder, Levincontents ::= <sequence of byte-length minus 4 characters>is in the original.  It should be:contents ::= <sequence of byte-length minus 12 characters>Sorry.Roy␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀*start*00890 00024 US Date: 4 March 1981 11:25 am PST (Wednesday)From: Schroeder.PASubject: Maybe parse header fort toc should accept only first field encountered.To: Levin, Brotz---------------------------Date: 3 March 1981 9:52 pm PST (Tuesday)From: Hamilton.ES