lected wisdom from Laurel 6 testersTo: Brotz, Birrell, Levin, TaftReply-To: Schroedercc: Horning, SchroederWell, I invited comment -- so I shouldn't complain when I get it.  Here's asummary.++++++++++++++++++++KUDOS1) I love the modeless editor.  This goes without saying, since we designed muchthe same interface into Star.  (However you really should get rid of the "balancebeam" method of placing the caret.  Always append.  Or at least make it anoption.  Very error prone. -- Dave Smith2) I love the ability to EASILY copy existing text.  Just push the Shift key downand select the text to copy.  Wonderful!  Much, much better than Bravo's orStar's.  In fact, I'm going to try to get it into Star.  For the first time ever on theAlto, it really is easier to copy from existing text than to type it. -- Dave Smith3) I love type-over replacement.  A real time-saver.  This will probably not gointo Star (sigh) because it is just not compatible with Star's concepts.  But it sureworks well for you folks. -- Dave Smith4) Overall, I really like the system - good work! -- Mike Trigoboff5) I never encounter any bugs in the software you guys release so, indesperation, I pass along this trivial observation.  (Appears below)  The care youtake in making your releases really frustrates us nit pickers.a -- Chuck Geschke6) I've been meaning to tell you:  SearchMail is the greatest thing since slicedbread!  Thanks! -- Bruce Hamilton SUGGESTIONS/BUGS1) I have written an itty-bitty program to change between white-on-black andblack-on-white  The program is available as [rain]<Hamilton>laurel>Flip.(mesalaurel). -- Bruce Hamilton 2) a brief set of rules for preparing programs for the RUN button. -- BillMcKeeman3) an understandable model of the button behavior.  Example: using the middlebutton to attempt to expand the bottom window when the system has warned thatsomething is about to wipe it out.  And I think there are situations where eachof buttons 1, 2 and 3 mean DO IT. -- Bill McKeeman 4) an "AutomaticUpdate" entry in the profile might be a good default for themasses.  It seems to me that it is those least able to recover from the self-imposedtrouble of an out-of-date program that are most likely to procrastinate doing whatis necessary to keep an up-to-date version on their disk.  It would also keep agood version on the public machines for which nobody in particular takesresponsibility. -- Bill McKeeman5) a profile entry like "InitialBoundary" similar to "Boundary" which wouldbring up Laurel with the specified window boundaries -- Bob Weissman6) a Sort command (or subprogram) to sort a message file chronologically -- BobWeissman7) I have the following lines in my user.cm:	[LAUREL]	Boundary: 0, 12, 19, 16	Boundary: 1, 1, 0, 0	Boundary: 2, 0, 1, 0	Boundary: 3, 0, 0, 1	Boundary: 8, 12, 35, 0	Boundary: 9, 12, 0, 35When I invoke COM+8 or COM+9, sometimes it leaves the upper window thesame size and sometimes it makes it a little smaller.  The latter seems to happenmost often when manual size adjustments via the control point are interspersed. Sometimes COM+0 does this too.  Am I missing something? -- Dave Smith8) When I type BACKSPACE with the shift key held down, it deletes forward! This is very annoying because one of the most frequent times I make typos iswhen I am typing an all uppercase word, like "BACKSPACE", which I do withmy little finger held on the Shift key.  Nice try, but that one just doesn't work. Please at least make it an option. -- Dave Smith9) I find it a minor irritation with Laurel that my copies of my own messages getflagged with a question mark when retrieved back from the Grapevine.  Thequestion mark flag should indicate those messages that I haven't yet read, NOTjust copies of my own messages coming back for record-keeping purposes.  Infact, it would also be nice if copies of my own messages did not count as "newmail" in my mailbox;  but that is less of an aggravation.    Would it be easy toleave off the question mark on copies, at least as an option? -- Lyle Ramshaw10) It would be nice if there could be such a thing as delayed delivery mail. That is, one could add message header fields, Delivery-Date and Delivery-Time,which would permit one to schedule delivery up to, say, a year in the future. Such mail could also, perhaps, be cancelled no later than five minutes inadvance of the scheduled delivery time.  The effect of the Delivery Date andTime is to cause the same effect as if the user had invoked Deliver at the statedDate and Time.  What would this be useful for?  There are a number ofexamples.  One could send out a batch of regularly scheduled announcements,such as Forum announcements, at the beginning of each month, with deliverydelayed until the beginning of the week in question, and a reminder scheduledfor noon on the same day.  People could schedule reminders for themselves. --Martin Haeberli11) editing in brackets -- Mike Trigoboff12) In SearchMail, could you provide something that just searched the headerfield(s) chosen?  Like if I wanted to select all my msgs from LaurelSupport, or allthe msgs I sent, or all with a particular subject.  The search would run a lotfaster if it didn't have to needlessly search the body of each msg.  (The way itworks now is valuable too - this is a request for an additional capability.) --Mike Trigoboff13) while "Move to" does a "Delete" as a subcommand, it does not do a "Displayafter Delete" when that is enabled.  It seems natural and desireable for it to do so.-- Forest Baskett14) PROBLEM WITH "Reply-To":  The sender and answerer both are required totry think about the insoluble question of who will be interested in the responsesto the original message.  Then, they HAVE TO DO EDITING IN THE MOSTCOMMON CASE, which is that everyone the message is sent to will be interestedin the answers, in which case either the sender or the answerer has to delete the"Reply-To" line.  THIS IS BAD DESIGN.  The whole point of the ANSWERcommand is that you should NOT have to do editing on the address in the mostcommon case!ALTERNATIVE APPROACH  (Mild version):  Require confirmation whenREPLYING to a distribution list! (Don't we already do this? MDS)  This isdownright obvious.  The lack of this could actually be considered a logical bugin the current Laurel.  It might even be worth requiring DOUBLE confirmation,as does copydisk:  "Are you REALLY sure?"ALTERNATIVE APPROACH  (Strong version):  The ANSWER command simplydoes not copy distribution list expressions.  If the answerer wants to reply to a dl, he has to edit the dl expression back into the address.  I would favor thisapproach. -- Joe Becker15) In many situations, Laurel treats the middle mouse button as <esc> but notfor files or subsystem name completion in the bottom window.  I find it mildlyinconsistent. -- Chuck Geschke16) (In the spirit of "last chance")  I like forward-delete a lot, but Ifumble-finger it more than any other feature, and the results can be modestlydevastating:  If I am typing a few capital letters, and want to backspace,  I'mlikely to forget to let go of the shift key.  If it's a single character, that's not toobad.  If a single word, the greedy algorithm gobbles up the whole next word,perhaps lines below.  Wouldn't normally be considered a problem, except that:	1. UNDO doesn't work, since it would back up to before the current		typein.	2. Even if it worked, at full speed, I might type too far ahead for it to be		useful.I have no suggestions at all; is there anything anyone can think of to make thisless damaging? -- Dan Swinehart17) I've recently written a couple of handy bcd's to run in Laurel, and I'm surethe rest of the world will, too.  Do you plan to coordinate all this software, orshould there be a Laurel subdirectory of MesaLib, or should people just blastmsgs out to LaurelUsers^ when they've come up with something handy? --Bruce Hamilton18) Laurel 6T33 has a rather annoying habit of not putting the selection where Ibug if I don't leave the mouse in one place for a certain amount of time afterbugging.  Is this intentional? -- Olmstead19) I just got oopsed several times because my disk filled up.  These are suchgross cases.  I think Laurel should peek ahead a bit more when it is snarfing upfiles and such. -- Hal Murray *start*00718 00024 US Date: 19 March 1981 11:52 am PST (Thursday)From: Schroeder.PASubject: SearchMail BugTo: Brotz---------------------------Date: 19 March 1981 9:37 am PST (Thursday)From: Weissman.PASubject: SearchMail BugTo: LaurelSupportReply-To: Weissmancc: WeissmanI started up SearchMail under Laurel 6T33 and got the search string prompt. Then I decided I wanted to do a Mail file command first, so I just typed a CR toSearchMail, figuring a null string would terminate it.  Instead, it entered aninfinite (or very long?) loop, flashing "Malformed search string" and ticking thegrandfather clock.  I had to swat out of Laurel.------------------------------------------------------------*start*00633 00024 US Date: 19 March 1981 8:38 pm PST (Thursday)From: Murray.PASubject: AccessList checkingTo: LaurelImp^Reply-To: Murraycc: Redell, MurrayI use Grapevine to do access control in several places.  Now that I have figuredout what I wanted to do and split the code out into another module, I havediscovered that it's really quite simple.  Have you considered adding a routine ofthat sort to one of your interfaces?  I called it ValidMemberOfGroup.I'll give you a pointer to my code if you are interested, but I'd also be interestedto see if you came up with the same collection of return codes as I did.*start*00390 00024 US Date: 11 May 1981 1:55 pm PDT (Monday)From: McKeeman.PASubject: (=) <=> [=] {=} "=" '='To: BrotzDoug,In the grand and glorious future:Considering my sloppy fingers and loose m