plus patch is a step forward -- the automatic Reply-Toseemed like the most effective tool you were likely to have in the war againstnerds -- and people get real used to confirming things until they happen.  Didpeople really find it difficult to delete the Reply-To line?  I suppose.Assuming you intend to keep this approach, it brings up another issue -- theconfirmation thing, which inherently increases the temporal modefulness of thesystem -- either you confirm or deny, but no other actions are available to youat the time you're doing it.   The "blue button" approach overrides someconfirmation requests before they happen, but others remain.  (We've discussedthis sort of thing before)  Here's an alternative approach that remains modeless: When a situation requiring confirmation arises, blink and moan as now, andignore the request.  Then replace the original menu item with one or severalmore powerful ones, possibly including one to forget the whole thing.  Thiscorresponds approximately to the current handling of Hardcopy.  Put the mostlikely response at the position of the original, if it's not too dangerous, or put theone that cancels under the original, if it is.  Now temporal modes have againbeen translated into spatial ones, which (shall we pray) is wonderful.A simpler thing to do is to more widely publicize the cycling capability of theGet command through .form files, so I can make one with Reply-To in it in thefirst place.Here's something else, more or less related, that I've wanted to be easier -- it'svery specialized, but it happens all the time (you asked for it by diddlingfeatures at this late date):  I'd like to have a keyboard command to delete(probably by expanding the pending-delete selection?) the entire line containingthe current pending-delete selection.  This is where I don't want to cc themessage to anybody at all.  With this feature you could leave Reply-To in andmake it very easy to delete it.  There's probably a generalization of this feature,with respect to other kinds of selections, that makes sense.  I know:  ctrl-NEXT. I can do it with the mouse but it takes a motion to the mouse,  motion of themouse to the line, and two clicks (three unless I'm clever) to get rid of the line.User programming!  But ship it anyhow!Dan*start*00522 00024 US Date: 4 April 1981 7:18 pm PST (Saturday)From: Ayers.PASubject: Laurel Six banging on a Spruce server which is not spoolingTo: LaurelSupportReply-To: Ayerscc: Brotz, MurrayToday I observed Laurel Six trying to send a hardcopy to Rockhopper when Ihad disabled spooling.Laurel kept retrying so fast that Spruce was totally busy sending the "Spooling isdisabled please try again later" message and went for extended periods withoutbeing able to print.This is very bad citizenship.Bob*start*00280 00024 US Date: 7 April 1981 11:53 am PST (Tuesday)From: McKeeman.PASubject: Toggling Move toTo: BrotzDoug,It is a nit, but left-bugging "Move to" brings up the name of TOC file, and thencomplains when you confirm it.  'Twould be better to skip it?s/Bill*start*00512 00024 US Date: 8 April 1981 9:25 am PST (Wednesday)From: Swinehart.PASubject: to {...} brackets in CopyTo: LaurelSupport, Brotzcc: SwinehartThese brackets should probably supply as default a directory-stripped version ofthe from field, rather than the last file name used in a previous copy command. I think that the from fields of Get and Copy should also be shared, but maybethere's a reason you don't do that.  (I remember a kludge for turning a Get into aCopy -- did that survive?)*start*00470 00024 US Date: 8 April 1981 6:27 pm PST (Wednesday)From: Haeberli.PASubject: Files.laurelTo: LaurelSupportReply-To: Haeberlicc: HaeberliThe rename command provided by Files.laurel has two faults:a) It fails to effect the rename in the file's leader page; it only changes thesystem directory.b) if I (accidentaly) rename Foo Foo'  the command