rt of the work.  I would put thosetables right there in the way so they have to be explicitly skipped over to beavoided.General Summary.  Publish it.Now for a little bitching and moaning.(pg 2) The dividing line between compiler and back-end is not clearly drawn.Moreover the n-language, m-machine strategy gets somewhat more complicatedas n and m increase.  The reader would be interested in what class of languages,and what class of machines fit into the n or m.  Lisp? Snobol? Prolog? -- A Lispmachine?  A Turing machine?  Or perhaps it works only for dialects of Pascaland single address machines.  On page 14 the claim of "many machines" needsmore precision.  (pg 2)  The underlined emphasis is unstylish and also incorrect.  The most thatcan be said is that there are good reasons to do optimizations on the intermediatecode.  Because, by working VERY hard, one could push more than is reasonableinto the intermediate code optimizer.  What can be said is that, if N is theanticipated number of back-ends, it is worth putting things into the intermediatecode optimizer that are not (roughly speaking) N-times harder to do there.(pg 3-9)  Only about 1/2 of this stuff is worth reading.  A diagram would bebetter than all of section 2.   Most of us that care about the topic can figure outwhat code sequences make sense for what languages.  The tricks aboutconditionals do need to be emphaized, however.(pg 4-7)  To repeat myself, his seems summarizable by saying that "it is moreefficient to put patterns in a table rather than in code".  By and large this is arehash of the concept of local optimization.  The paper will be stronger with amuch shorter section here.  I definitely get the impression it is written forsomeone who understands nothing about optimization.  That is the wrongaudience.(pg 7-9)  The implicit assumption is that it is time for which the optimization isbeing done, and that perhaps space will come along with it.  That is not alwaysthe case and deserves mention.  And, later, space is used as the measure ofsuccess.(pg 9)  "backs up" is a slightly unfortunate choice of words because might read"backtracking" into it.  It is the pointer that is backed up so far as I can tell.(pg 9-16)  Unredeeminly boring.  The authors might question whether thismaterial is worth including.  What is the point?  You are recapping thereasoning that led to the results.  It is like finding the musings of amathematician in the middle of a proof.  A better approach is to key on the mostsignificant frequencies, and say where they came from.(pg 16-17)  The first test is claimed to be "independent of both source languageand target machine".  Just so!  It is therefore an irrelevant measure.  Unless thereis evidence that it makes for a better result, there is no point in publishing thefigures.  A more homely example of this kind of reasoning is: "We knocked down17% of all the straw men we set up."  There is no way to know if the ADI 0improvement, for example, is an artifact of a dumb compiler that should neverhave emitted it, or a substantive problem now resolved.  The subsequentcomments for PDP-11 code are better.  It would be better to merely present thelatter, and then point out that they do not differ much from figures derived fromEM-1 alone.(pg 18)  The argument about INC makes no sense at all.  The substance of it isthat in a nice clean intermediate machine, we can depend on doing these thingswithout wierd side effects.  But then the code emitter will just have to undo thework because its real INC instruction is in fact wierd, and does not have exactlythe same semantics as the intermediate INC.  A more serious consequence of thisnature is that constant folding might cause an interrupt at compile time thatshould occur at run time.  How is this handled?------------------------------------------------------------*start*00986 00024 US Date: 16 April 1981 2:35 pm PST (Thursday)From: Horning.paSubject: Confirmation ConsistencyTo: Brotzcc: LaurelImp^Doug,Right button (Blue) selection in 6T39 does indeed confirm the first set of bracketsfor Copy.  However, for the other command with two sets of brackets(Substitute), it confirms both.For neither command is there a single action to confirm both sets of bracketsafter a left button (Red) or Com+s activation.I think you should strive for consistency here.  I have a slight operationalpreference for Blue as "repeat the command with the same operands" (I do a fairnumber of repeated substutions, changing only the selection in between), and aslight explanatory preference for Blue as "Red followed by Yellow," so won'tscream loudly if either interpretation is picked (consistently).Blue Get, etc., requires an additional confirmation if there is an undeliveredmessage, which is consistent with either interpretation.Jim H.*start*00610 00024 US Date: 21 April 1981 10:48 am PST (Tuesday)Sender: McKeeman.PASubject: Laurel DocumentationTo: BrotzFrom: McKeemanFor your pleasure.					mouse					 ........					 ||					 ||					 ''''''''		Left			Middle			Right		Red			Yellow			Blue		-----------------------------------------------------		select			select				extend		chr/line		word/para			selectionshift		select			select				extend		chr/line		word/para			source		as source		as source			selectioncontrol	select			select				extend		chr/line		word/para			deletion		for deletion		for deletion			selection*start*00756 00024 US Date: 22 April 1981 12:39 pm PST (Wednesday)Sender: McKeeman.PASubject: Laurel Matrix, forgot a lineTo: Brotz, BurstallFrom: McKeeman				   mouse				    L M R				   \  |  /					 ........					 ::					 ::					 ''''''''		Left			Middle			Right		Red			Yellow			Blue		-----------------------------------------------------		select			select				extend		chr/line		word/para			selectionshift		select			select				extend		chr/lin