to speak.  So I wrote aprogram that, when run from the bottom window of Laurel 6, reconfiguresthe keyboard to approximate a Dvorak keyboard (I only permuted the boundingbox of the alphabet:  numbers and all special function keys are unchanged).The program is on 	[Ivy]<Ramshaw>Dvorak>Dvorak.laurel.Running it once will turn your keyboard into a Dvorak one; and running itagain will put it back to normal.  The file	[Ivy]<Ramshaw>Dvorak>Dvorak.Pressis a picture of the new arrangement of the keys, for use as a cheat sheetduring your first few hours of Dvorak'ing, should you be curious/foolishenough to want to experiment with this along with me,Lyle*start*00660 00024 US Date: 8 May 1981 5:28 pm PDT (Friday)From: Daniels.PASubject: Re: Laurel 6 is releasedTo: Diplomacy^.ES, Diplomacy^.PAReply-To: DanielsNow that Laurel 6 is officially here, you may wish to try the Hardcopy Form forDiplomacy messages.  You can find it on[Phylum]<Daniels>Diplomacy>LaurelProfileSlice.  To use it, simply include it inyour Laurel profile, then when you go to print Diplomacy messages, use"Diplomacy" for the form (see the Laurel 6 manual for more details.)  Several ofus have been using it for quite some time, and it seems to be about right, butfeel free to change it to suit your own fancy.			-- Andy. --*start*00676 00024 US Date: 12 May 1981 10:05 am PDT (Tuesday)From: Schwartz.PASubject: SearchMailTo: LaurelSupportcc: SchwartzThe released version of SearchMail puts a black box character on my screenwhen I type ESC to terminate the search pattern.  I don't remember earlierversions doing this.VictorSearchMail selects all messages in current mail file that contain the "pattern".Special characters for use in the search pattern are:   # = any char; * = any string; @ = any alpha; & =  alpha string;   ! = any non-alpha; ~ =  non-alpha string; 'x = use "x"ESC terminates the search pattern.Type search pattern: BrodieMessages containing pattern: 178