tended recipient) is away on atrip or home sick, the delay could be weeks, and an important message might notget through on time.Phil Petit rather frequently receives messages for me, usually from people whoknow the correct spelling of my name but who simply mistyped it.  I appreciatehis forwarding them to me immediately, and hope he continues to do so.  I willcontinue to forward those I receive for Phil to him.	Teri PettitP.S.  As you like analogies, I would contend that most misaddressed laurelmessages are analogous to letters which arrive in the post for a former roommate,whose new address you know.  In those cases, you do not mark out the addressand let the post office figure out what to do.  You substitute the new address andmark Please Forward.*start*00354 00024 US Date: 12 May 1981 11:51 am PDT (Tuesday)From: Petit.PASubject: Re: Wrong numbers in LaurelIn-reply-to: Pettit's message of 12 May 1981 10:49 am PDT (Tuesday)To: Pettitcc: Brotz, PetitYes, I certainly intend to continue forwarding any of your mail which I get, inspite of what anyone tells me I should do instead.--Phil*start*00422 00024 US Date: 12 May 1981 1:46 pm PDT (Tuesday)From: Horning.paSubject: Laurel 6.1 Suggestion: Hardcopy - Printer, Form, Copies, etc.To: Brotzcc: HorningDoug,It would be nice if the submenu command brackets had the same "autoscrolling"feature on Red as other brackets, so one could simply hold down Red to see thechoices.Autoscrolling (or clicking Red on) Copies should just count up.Jim H.*start*00340 00024 US Date: 12 May 1981 2:50 pm PDT (Tuesday)From: Woods.PASubject: To: BrotzI've haven't had time to do more than skim the Laurel 6 manual, but in doing soI saw nothing about the various interesting characters available, and I thinkthey would have stood out enough to notice.  An oversight?	-- Don.*start*00425 00024 US Date: 13 May 1981 3:03 pm PDT (Wednesday)From: Brotz.PASubject: Re: Wrong number