: AllEOS^.eos, AllXRCC^.xrccFrom: Brotz.pa, Schroeder.pa, Levin.pa, Birrell.pacc: LaurelSupport.paReply-To: LaurelSupport.paThis message announces the release of "Laurel 6" to message system users in theEOS and XRCC registries.  Users of all previous versions of Laurel, XLaurel,and LaurelX should convert to Laurel 6 as soon as possible.  Previous versionsare no longer supported, and may stop working due to changes in the messagetransport system.  Laurel 6 will run on all Alto configurations that could runLaurel 5.1 or LaurelX and on all Dolphins and Dorados in Alto emulation mode.If you encounter any problems with Laurel 6 please send a message toLaurelSupport.PA.UPDATING TO LAUREL 6Laurel 6 is stored in the <Laurel> directory on the following file servers:     RoseBowl -- In Pasadena, Net 40     Aklak -- In Toronto, Net 33To convert from an earlier version of Laurel to Laurel 6:    1.  Pick the server nearest (in the Internet) to your customary workstation.    2.  Retrieve (with FTP) the file "<Laurel>Laurel.cm" from that server.    3.  Type "@Laurel.cm@ to the Alto executive.If you are not a current user of Laurel, but wish to try Laurel 6, then follow thesame instructions, but use the command file "<Laurel>LaurelNewUser.cm".FOR USERS OF Laurel 6T*'sSome of you have been testing pre-release versions of Laurel 6 for us.  These areidentified by the herald "Laurel 6T*", for * IN [1..42].  It is important that youalso convert to the "official" released version of Laurel 6.  You should also makesure that you have the most recent versions of the Runnable ".Laurel" files.  Theeasiest way to be sure is to present the following command to the Alto executive:     FTP server dir/c Laurel ret/c Laurel.run ret/u *.Laurelwhere "server" is chosen as above.FOR USERS OF LaurelXLaurelX is an ASD-produced version of Laurel 5.1 that contains a BravoX-styleeditor.  (Do not confuse this with XLaurel, which is a version of Laurel 5.1designed to run on extended memory Altos.) To make the Laurel 6 editor similarto the LaurelX editor, add the following line to your Laurel profile:        Editor: modelessand then restart Laurel 6.DOCUMENTATIONComplete documentation for Laurel 6 exists as the file <Laurel>Laurel.press oneach of the above servers.  THIS MANUAL HAS 112 PAGES!  DON'T TRY TOPRINT IT ON YOUR LOCAL PRINTER DURING NORMAL WORKING HOURS. We suggest that each organization arrange to reproduce hard copies of thismanual for local distribution.  Users should wait for an announcement from theirlocal support organization that copies of the manual are available.   The Laurel 6user interface is generally upward compatible with previous versions of Laurel. Users of previous versions should have no trouble using Laurel 6. (The Laurel 6 manual comes in two parts, Laurel.press and LaurelScreen.press. Both should be printed and the second inserted after the table of contents in thefirst.  The manual is laid out for two-sided printing.  A separate file containingonly the modeless editor summary at the end of the Laurel manual is also storedon EditSummary.press.)SUMMARY OF CHANGESThe facilities available in Laurel 5.1 and LaurelX have been merged in Laurel 6. Where features of those two systems were in conflict, there is usually a profileoption in Laurel 6 that chooses between them.  Laurel 6 also has a significantnumber of changes and improvements over Laurel 5.1 and LaurelX.The profile options Authenticate:, Herald:, HeraldFont:, Logo:, LogoFont:, Poll:,and DisplayErrorPups: are no longer recognized by Laurel.  The Authenticate:option has been subsumed by the Registry: entry in your profile.  The otherentries that deal with hardcopy options are subsumed by more general hardcopyforms.The arrangement of screen commands has been altered slightly from previousversions of Laurel.  The Delete command has been moved next to the Displaycommand, with the Hardcopy command now placed at the right margin.  The{brackets} for several commands, e.g., for Get and Put, are now located on asecond menu line that only becomes visible when you need it.  Just invokethese commands in the normal way; their {brackets} will appear automatically.The Laurel editor now comes in two flavors, modal and modeless.  The modaleditor is similar to the editor in Laurel 5.1; the modeless editor is similar to theone in LaurelX.  A large number of new editor commands are available in eithereditor.  By default, you get the modal editor.A new kind of selection, called shifted selection, is an alternative to type-in,whether you use the old-style editor or the newer modeless editor.  At any timethat Laurel expects type-in, you may hold down SHIFT, make a selection andthen lift up SHIFT.  The selection will be copied as though you had just typedit, and you may continue type-in.New screen commands, Copy and Run, are available.  Copy provides FTP-likeservices for both local and remote files.  Run allows you to run various programswhile still in Laurel.  These programs exist as *.laurel files on the <Laurel>directories.  By editing your Laurel profile (using Bravo or laurel) to include theline          RunPath: [server]<Laurel>(where "server" is the one you chose from the list above), you will tell Laurel toretrieve these programs when you first invoke them.  The program Chat.laurel,for example, turns your bottom window into a Chat typescript.  To try it(assuming that you've added "RunPath ... " to your profile and restarted Laurel),invoke the "Run" command, enter the word Chat into its brackets, and connect orlogin to your favorite server.*start*00481 00024 US Date: 8 May 1981 1:46 pm PDT (Friday)From: Brotz.PASubject: Re: Laurel 6 release for Laurel 6T usersTo: @Laurel6.dlcc: BrotzReply-To: BrotzThe command line given in the release message for upating to Laurel 6 was inerror.The correct command line isFTP/-e server dir/c Laurel ret/u *.laurelThis will update all of your official *.laurel programs without distrubing anyunofficial ones that you may have.Sorry for any inconvenience.-- Doug*start*00245 00024 US Date: 19 May 1981 12:02 pm PDT (Tuesday)To: MeFrom: MeSubject: Laurel 6 file sizeLaurel 5.1 is 403 pages.  Laurel 6 is 569 pages.  Also, the laurel state file is alittle bit bigger.  About 180 pages more in total.*start*02215 00024 US Date: 20 May 1981 11:27 am PDT (Wednesday)From: Bergsteinsson.ESSubject: Suggestions for Laurel ChangesTo: LaurelSupport.pacc: BergsteinssonThese are sort of a nit, but you might put them into the hopper of things toconsider if you are going to do another Laurel release.The ESC in laurel (when Laurel is not waiting for an ESC to confirm some actionor signal the end of input) repeats the last editing command in the compositionwindow.  The following commands work the way one would expect.	a - appends same text to current selection	b - brackets current selection	d - deletes current selection again	i - inserts same text in from of current selection	r - replaces current selection with same text	t - inserts time stamp in from of current selectionThe following commands work other than one would expect.	e - executes last editing command according to rules above		recommended action:  None (repeat of "e" is a NOP)	f - executes last editing command according to rules above		recommended action: Search forward from the current selection to		find the next occurance of the text string	s - replaces current selection with text which was selected at the end of	    the last "s" command		recommended action: re-execute substitute logic using the current		selection and the same values for old and new text strings as were		used on the "s" command just done	u - undoes the last editing command		recommended action: reject undo after e, f, s, g, and p, and leave		processing of ESC after "u" as is.	g - looks like the text insertion of a get acts as a repeatable command, but		it is not redoing a Get using the current selection		recommeded action: reject ESC after g	p - executes last editing command according to rules above		recommeded action: reject ESC after pIf the last command was rejected with an error message, reject the ESC, ratherthan go back to a command which preceeded the operator error.Of all these recommendations, the one which is the most useful would be torepeat a Find.  (Ungrateful wench, aren't I - give me an inch and I want amile.  Oh well, at least you know we are out here using all these wonderful newfeatures.)Linda*start*00503 00024 US Date: 19 May 1981 5:52 pm PDT (Tuesday)From: Halbert.PASubject: bug when running out of disk space while hardcopyingTo: LaurelSupportI was hardcopying a long message, and ran out of disk space while Laurel wasgenerating the press file.  Instead of dying gracefully, Laurel did an OOPS andasked me to report the following error to you:signal 033601 in(that's it; great, huh?).Seems like it should just abort the hardcopy and tell the user to delete something.--Dan*start*00213 00024 US Date: 19 May 1981 5:57 pm PDT (Tuesday)From: Halbert.PASubject: previous message bug reportTo: LaurelSupportThat's Laurel 6 I was telling you about.  Sorry I didn't say before. --Dan*start*00900 00024 US Date: 21 May 1981 10:03 am PDT (Thursday)From: Ramshaw.PASubject: Laurel suggestionTo: Brotzcc: RamshawDoug, I request that some future Laurel have a feature that allows the turningoff of the Shift-backspace feature.  I am typing a long message of comments onthe Interpress standard at this point, and there are lots of times when I amholding down the shift key and typing a long word  (such as ADDNEWID). When I make a mistake in typing, I naturally type backspace, and it does theWRONG THING, eating up the following text instead.  Very annoying.  Ofcourse, there are other times when shift-backspace is quite conveni