Maxc as a text file.If your file is less than 64K characters and is text, then you can store it throughLaurel by Get'ting and Put'ting.  If the file is over 64K characters and is binary,you can store it on Maxc with the Laurel Copy command.  If the file is text andover 64K characters, then you have to use FTP.Note that IFS's do not suffer from this disease, since they have Alto OS's.-- Doug*start*00416 00024 US Mail-from: Arpanet host CMU-10A rcvd at 31-MAR-81 1824-PSTDate: 31 March 1981 2122-EST (Tuesday)From: Xerox AltoTo: Brotz.PA at PARC-MAXCSubject:  Re: Looking for Laurel directoriesSender: Ivor.Durham at CMU-10A (S200AL00)In-Reply-To:  Brotz.PA's message of 31 Mar 81 20:12-ESTMessage-Id: <31Mar81 212231 AL00@CMU-10A>The Universities have <Laurel> directories on their IFSes.Ivor*start*00331 00024 US Date: 1 June 1981 8:28 am PDT (Monday)From: Swinehart.PASubject: Laurel for universitiesTo: Brotzcc: SwinehartDid we decide what to do?  Could I "release" the programs, and wait on the Blueand White for the manuals?  Laurel 6 will work OK if the universities have thelatest IFS installed won't it?*start*01173 00024 US Date: 1 June 1981 9:26 am PDT (Monday)From: Taft.PASubject: Read-only remote mail files?To: Brotzcc: Schroeder, Levin, Birrell, TaftIt occurred to me that using the Leaf remote mail file capability might be aneffective way to browse the CSL-notebook, whose summaries are kept in a mailfile on Ivy.  So I invoked MailFile on [Ivy]<CSL-notebook>Notebook-index.mail. It worked like a charm.A while later, I began wondering where Laurel had put the TOC.  I huntedaround and finally found it -- on [Ivy]<CSL-Notebook> !  This worked onlybecause I am a wheel on Ivy and can create files anywhere.So I continued the experiment by disabling my Ivy wheel status and tryingagain.  This time, MailFile on [Ivy]<CSL-notebook>Notebook-index.mail yieldedthe rather strange error message "Disk errors.  Get mail file failed