4 US Date: 26 June 1981 4:39 pm PDT (Friday)From: McKeeman.PATo: BrotzSubject: hardcopy glitchSee the circled spot on the sheet in your clover box.-----Subject: Software Engineers - SPECTRUMPrintForm: WangLetterHeading: Software EngineersFrom: McKeemanTo: FagenbaumDate: 26 June 1981 1:42 pm PDT (Friday)Joel FagenbaumAssociate Editor, SPECTRUMIEEE, Inc.345 East 47th StreetNew York, NY 10017						26 June 1981Dear Joel,Jim Horning passed on to me the draft of your essay on Software Engineering.  He knew that I would be interested because of my new role as Chairman of theFaculty at the Wang Institute.  I am pleased to see the topic catching yourattention and grateful for the exposure it gives to our new programme.  I hopeyou do not mind my giving you my reactions your article and some thoughts Ihave had on the same subject.  It is intended to help you in your doublydifficult task of documenting, as an outsider, something only beginning to beunderstood by insiders.I try to stay aware of the meaning of the title:  Engineer, "one who appliesingenuity", and Software, which was a catchy way to say not-hardware, andreally signifies the information held in, and processed by, the hardware.In contrast to the undifferentiated skill set of		programming+hardware design+systems engineeringyou postulated, we at WIGS have decided that a Software Engineer must befirstly skilled in programming and also, but secondarily, know enough abouthardware, computer application areas, and managing people to produce highquality systems of programs.  It is my personal conviction that what we will do isbetter modelled by a medical school than an academic curriculum in ComputerScience.A major difficulty faced by the software engineer is an unusual need forbreadth.  As you note, inexorably computers are going to be everywhere.  It isnot likely that a single Software Engineer is going to be a robotics expert,proficient in business data processing, a network communications analyst, asolver of integral equations and a VLSI designer.  We will, as do our medicalanalogs, have specialties.  Our approach at WIGS is to define a core curriculumaround the universal skills we all need, and then differentiate with electives andproject courses to help our students develop one or more specialties. ( I willarrange for a pile of material representing the present state of the curriculum tobe sent to you.)Changing the subject, I quote from my recent letter to Harlan Mills, on the topicof management skills for Software Engineers:"One management problem arises in that complexity drives us to using teams.  Nomatter what the tolerance for complexity some (perhaps remarkable) individualhas, (we know now that) there are much lower limits on the acceptablecomplexity of the interactions within teams.  This has led to the anomaly ofsystems that can be built well by one person, or many people, but by no size ofteam in between.  It seems to me that the management curriculum must focus onthose techniques that we have found close the anomalous gap.  Of course,complex systems are going to be built in any case; the measure of success of themanagement techniques is the quality of the resulting product.The problem is in a sense recursive; the production of automated managementtools is within our technical expertise.  We apply our own wares to our ownproblems.  For example, I regard the cost models from TRW, and variousintegration and testing tools as within the nascent management curriculum."A characteristic of information systems which is well-known, but frequentlyignored is that, like buildings, one expects to change them over a period of time. An architect would not call adding a wing to his hospital "maintenance".  In theanalogous situation, we software engineers do.  The important thing is not, ofcourse, the words used, but the preparations made.  Making a system modifiableis much harder than just making it work.Valuing software is another dimly understood area where we must developexpertise.  Software has cost to build, cost to replace, market value, rental value,(perhaps) taxable assessed value, and so on.  Although we have a good deal oftolerance now, in the longer run the software engineer must be able to makeclosely reasoned economic decisions.Well, I can obviously go on at length.  The details are not the point of my letterto you.  Rather I hope to reinforce the seriousness with which we regard the taskof building the practice of Software Engineering.  It's short history is admirablyexposed by Professor Hoare in his Turing Lecture (see the February 81Communications of the ACM).  I summarize it all by Thoreau's dictum"Simplicity, simplicity, simplicity!".  						Cordially,						W. M. McKeemancc: WIGS*start*00989 00024 US Date: 29 June 1981 5:12 pm PDT (Monday)From: Schroeder.PASubject: A real bug?To: Brotzcc: SchroederFileIn Use from CoreStreams when IntPress attempted to open a write stream onSwatee.---------------------------Date: 29 June 1981 5:00 pm PDT (Monday)From: Beeson.ESSubject: Error ReportTo: LaurelSupport.PAI was "hardcopying" a rather long message with a form and a printer that weredifferent than what was in my Laurel.profile.Laurel 6  Alto II XM (010#073#) with Ram only MDS: 00 Banks: 100000 code:000051Signal 033601 in CoreStreamsmsg 000025, msg^                            BackStop, 003550Signaller, 000521Signaller, 001102CoreStreams, 002703CoreStreams, 000256IntPress, 002755IntHardcopyCom, 002200IntHardcopyCom, 000340IntHardcopyCom, 001272IntTrackMain, 001747IntTrackMain, 001250IntTrackMain, 001112IntTrackMain, 000704LaurelNub, 000122DebugNub, 000334------------------------------------------------------------*start*01130 00024 US Date: 1 July 1981 1:41 pm PDT (Wednesday)From: GWilliams.PATo: BrotzSubject: The "reply-to" field fill-inMail-from: Arpanet host SRI-KL rcvd at 1-JUL-81 1053-PDTDate:  1 Jul 1981 1051-PDTFrom: LARSON at SRI-KLSubject: your messageTo: GWilliams at PARC-MAXC  I noticed that the headers to your message included a "reply-to:"that did not include a site name.  I suspect that you did not intendit to be this way, since some net sites would get confused and try toreply to "GWilliams" as a local address at their site.  This is apotentially serious problem, since you may not get mail that peopleanswer from other net sites.  Your "from:" was correct, so you couldactually eliminate the "reply-to:" and other mail programs will replyto the "from:".	AlanSubject: Re: your messageIn-reply-to: Your message of 1 Jul 1981 1051-PDTTo: LARSON at SRI-KLcc: GWilliamsYes, but unfortunately, my mail program requires me to add the reply-to: whensending to distribution lists. The reply-to: is added for me. I can edit it  buthadn't. I'll see if our mail people want to address this.Glen*start*00606 00024 US Date: 7 July 1981 5:17 pm EDT (Tuesday)Sender: MarkWilson.EOSFrom: MarkWilsonSubject: Hardcopy ProblemTo: LaurelSupport.PAcc: MarkWilsonI have had this problem on and off for some time where I cannot hardcopy fromLaurel.  I get the message "Printer not responding" in Laurel and the message onthe printer server screen is "Receiver timed out".  I am running Laurel 6.0 butthis happened with 5.0 as well, though not as persistently.  Our printer server isrunning Spruce 11.0 with a Penguin.Putting and Empressing Laurel messages is no fun.  Do you have anysuggestions?*start*00418 00024 US Date: 9 July 1981 2:19 pm PDT (Thursday)From: Lyon.PASubject: Re: Laurel 6 is releasedIn-reply-to: Brotz's message of 8 May 1981 1:03 pm PDT (Friday)To: LaurelSupportHere's a problem I encountered:The blinking caret can not be at the end of a selection that ends with a return.In particular, it is not possible to append a paragraph to a paragraph withoutcleaning up the interfaces.*start*00853 00024 U