ing those stored    on IFS's and those kept as standard initial disks in many locations.3.  From "helpful" users' disks.  These helpers initiate a new user to Laurel with    a "You probably would like this Help.mail file from my disk that I've been    saving for years."When Laurel 6 was released, the Laurel group took great pains to store theLaurel files on each IFS consistently.  We did not update any Basic Disks at thattime, since they are controlled by individual administrators.  Since then, entropyhas been working its nefarious deeds.Please examine any directories under your control to insure that Laurel 6, notLaurel 5.1 is there.  The creation date for both Laurel.run and Laurel.imageshould be 6-May-81.  Also make sure that Tutorial.mail is there, not Help.mail. Please do the same for any Basic Disks under your control.  I know for sure thatsome ancient versions are on Phylum, in Henrietta, and in Webster.  There maybe others.  There is not much we can do about number 3. above, but they arenot the major source of the infestation.Thank you for your help.Yours in the battle against entropy,-- Doug*start*01205 00024 US Date: 19 Aug. 1981 4:49 pm PDT (Wednesday)From: McNown.PASubject: Error ReportTo: LaurelSupport.PAHi, Guys (and perhaps Gals)...  I had called up Laurel and typed a 3 to get thenew message window.  I had created a two paragraph message to Mau withcopies to Miller.es and myself.  I had bugged deliver when i noticed that i hadno "er" on Miller.  I hit delete.  The "S" in subject was underscored.  I could notaccomplish an insert ahead of the ".es".  I thought that i was not in the basicmode so hit an exc to free the underscore.  I got the Butterfly looking PS and themessage to bug yellow.  It gives you a warm feeling to know that there is agroup that cares about the malfunctions.  This is a great place to work.  bobLaurel 6  Alto II XM (060#045#) with 2K Rom XMcode using XM MDS: 00Banks: 160000 code: 00