ce Maxc, Msg, LaurelSupport.pa,Tools environment, etc.That said, the files are on [Juniper]<DMS>Laurel>6>Manual>including  <DMS>Laurel>6>Manual>Laurel6-title.bravo  <DMS>Laurel>6>Manual>Laurel6-toc.bravo  <DMS>Laurel>6>Manual>LaurelScreen.press  <DMS>Laurel>6>Manual>Laurel6-1.bravo  <DMS>Laurel>6>Manual>Laurel6-2.bravo  <DMS>Laurel>6>Manual>Laurel6-3.bravo  <DMS>Laurel>6>Manual>Laurel6-4a.bravo  <DMS>Laurel>6>Manual>Laurel6-4b.bravo  <DMS>Laurel>6>Manual>Laurel6-5.bravo  <DMS>Laurel>6>Manual>Laurel6-6.bravo  <DMS>Laurel>6>Manual>Laurel6-7.bravo  <DMS>Laurel>6>Manual>Laurel6-8.bravo  <DMS>Laurel>6>Manual>Laurel6-9.bravo  <DMS>Laurel>6>Manual>Laurel6-a.bravo  <DMS>Laurel>6>Manual>laurel6-b.bravo  <DMS>Laurel>6>Manual>Laurel6-c.bravo  <DMS>Laurel>6>Manual>Laurel6-d.bravo  <DMS>Laurel>6>Manual>Laurel6-e.bravo  <DMS>Laurel>6>Manual>EditSummary.silThe above list shows the order in which these files should be put together toreconstruct the manual.  All .bravo files are in Bravo 7 format, the .sil file is theSIL input file for the editor summary at the end of the manual, and the .pressfile is the picture of the Laurel screen.  The Laurel6-n.bravo refers to chapter orAppendix n, where chapter 4 had to be split into two halves due to its largesize.  Laurel6-toc.bravo is the table of contents, which you will certainly have tomodify to reflect your new manual.The .bravo files have been tuned with Look Keep's and Page Breaks to obtain thefinal layout.  Each chapter begins on a right-hand page, and the precedingchapter may have been padded out with a blank page to insure this,  When youedit the files, these fine tunings will get in your way.There are corresponding .press files for each of the source files listed above.These files represent the final version of the Laurel Manual that is currently inthe pipeline for publication as a PARC/CSL Blue&White report, not the versionthat was widely distributed throught Xerox last May.  This version has beencleared for international release.  You should check on any rules governing thepublication of your translated version.If you have any questions, please ask.-- Doug*start*00557 00024 US Date: 28 Aug. 1981 4:22 pm PDT (Friday)From: Kierr.paSubject: Suggestion re bogus dl'sTo: LaurelSupportcc: BogusDL^If I try to send a message to a bogus dl, Laurel currently requires me to type<esc>.  (Laurel says "1 invalid name(BogusDL^).")  It seems that fairly oftenpeople type <esc> without realizing what will (not) happen and their messagegoes nowhere.  (Maybe they think that some name within the dl is bad?)  Ithink it would be better for Laurel to refuse to deliver a message with a bogus dladdressed.  /Robert*start*00954 00024 US Date: 31 AUG 1981 0924-PDTFrom: SHOCH.PASubject: Re: Laurel 6 in SwedenTo:   Brotzcc:   SHOCHIn response to your message sent  26 Aug. 1981 11:00 am PDT (Wednesday)Doug,Thanks for your recent note about Laurel's use in Europe.On the one hand, I am delighted that RX is using the Altoand Laurel within their operations in Europe -- in the UKand Sweden.  I already get messages from an occasional soulin Europe, and providing them with new versions of Laurel isin our interest.On the other hand, I don't know what to make of the lingeringASD probes in Sweden -- that's a problem to be worked out byOPD and RX.  OPD surely wants to wind them down, and RX feelsobliged to provide support.....  I view RX as the marketingunit, and we try to meet their needs;  but it surely requiressome joint planning.....Nothing profound in all this -- sorry I can't shed anyparticularly bright light.Best regards,john*start*00472 00024 US Date: 1 Sept. 1981 1:41 pm PDT (Tuesday)From: chance.ESSubject: Re: Add to @LaurelUsersIn-reply-to: Brotz.PA's message of 1 Sept. 1981 10:19 am PDT (Tuesday)To: Brotz.PAcc: chance, LaurelSupport.PADoug,I got this laurel from Mae Thomas' master laurel disk, which she gives to newpeople. 