eers of new communication and informationtechnology are continually developing systems that alter theway in which we go about our work.  Unfortunately there has beenlittle systematic study of the use and impacts of these developments.Design and implementation are often more driven by thecharacteristics of new technology than the needs of users.At Xerox, the opportunity exists to carefully examine the useand impacts of one such new office technology: electronic mail.A brief summary of such a study's focus and methods is providedbelow.Focus of Study     The Laurel messaging system was introduced at Xerox severalyears ago.  Since then much anecdotal evidence has been gatheredabout its use.  One study, conducted by Chuck Henderson, clearlyillustrates the potential of electronic mail to create wide rangingsocial and behavioral impacts in the office.  What is now neededis a more quantitative approach, which not only uncovers areas whereimpacts might lie, but also can highlight the direction andmagnitude of these impacts.  In particular, the study should provideinformation in three major areas:    1.  USES.  How the system is used must be carefully analyzed.        Frequency of use, facilities that are used or not used, who is        communicating with whom, what tasks are accomplished, in        what situations is the system used, etc. are all types of        information that will highlight potential impacts.    2.  IMPACTS.  Certain patterns of use will lead to different        kinds of impacts.  These should included both perceived        impacts of the system as well as externally observed impacts.        Perceived impacts include:  User judgements of impacts        on work efficiency and effectiveness, job satisfaction,        perceived changes in communication behaviors, etc.        Unobtrusive measures of actual impacts may include changes        in the communication patterns; i.e. who communicates with        whom, the frequency of interaction, the number of different        contacts, turnover and absenteeism, mobility in the         company in terms of promotions, etc.    3.  FACTORS PREDICTING USES AND THEIR IMPACTS.  In particular,        demographic characteristics of users, user attitudes and        expectations, characteristics of their jobs/tasks, as well        as department and organization variables all may play        a part in explaining/predicting uses and impacts.     By examining the relationships between these sets of variablesit is possible to gain an understanding of the impacts of electronic mail that might vary considerably from the imagesgleaned from the anecdotal evidence.  Statistical analysis can helpuncover relationships which are not intuitively obvious.     There are potentially hundreds of impacts of electronic mailuse.  This study will focus on those impacts which appear to haverelevance to the question of productivity, directly or indirectly.Benefits of the Proposed Study to Xerox     The proposed research will benefit Xerox in two critical areas:design and implementation.  These are briefly addressed below.     Design       Designers are continuously working to improve the utility of the Laurel messaging system.   Armed with such data as features which work or don't work, types of uses to which the system isput, and uses which are associated with negative consequences,these designers will be better able to provide a system which more closely meets the needs of end users.     Implementation     Little is known about the most appropriate strategies forintroducing electronic mail systems.  Relating user, usage, andimpact data can assist in the development of effective implementationstrategies.  For example, users with certain job characteristicsmight have unique needs for a messaging system, and thus requirean orientation which is tailored to these needs.  In addition,it may be the case that behaviors thought to be inappropriate(i.e. game playing, use for personal correspondence) actuallyhave positive consequences for individual users and the organizationas a whole.  Knowledge of these instances would be invaluablein the development of successful implementation strategies.General Research Methodology     The proposed study would follow a sequence of phases commonto field research endeavors.  By field research it is meantthat actual behaviors in a field setting form the core of dataupon which the study is based.  The phases include:     1.  IN-DEPTH INTERVIEWS.  Interviews with system designers        and users would be used to obtain very textured information        about both system use and organizational "culture".  This        information would then be used to development more         quantitative instruments which are both meaningful and         relevant to potential respondents.  These interviews can        also provide information regarding the availability of         existing sources of relevant data, including company        records, prior studies, system logs, etc.    2.  RESEARCH DESIGN.  After interviews are conducted, a detailed        research design can be developed.  Specifically, sampling        strategies, data collection methods, and data analysis        strategies can be planned.  Data collection and analysis        are briefly addressed below.  The sampling plan will be        devised with study objectives in mind.  Ideally a         representative sample of users and non-users would be        included in the study.  The inclusion of a control group        of non-users would permit much stronger statements about        the impacts of electronic mail by allowing many alternative        rival hypotheses to be ruled out.    3.  DATA COLLECTION.  While methods of data collection cannot        be specified until existing sources of data are carefully        evaluated, a general strategy can be outlined.  A        multi-operational approach to data collection will be        used.  That is, each single method of collecting data         suffers from unique strengths as well as weaknesses.        By incorporating several methods, strengths can be        capitalized upon while protecting against weaknesses.        Among methods likely to be employed are questionnaires        for obtaining user attitudes and perceptions, system logs        for obtaining usage data, and company records for obtaining        other user information.  In all cases, privacy and        confidentiality of respondents will be guarded.  Respondents        will be assured that responses will not be released,        except in statistical summary.  In addition, wherever         possible, the burden of effort on respondents will be        minimized.  A final guideline for data collection is that        whenever possible, the system itself will be used as a        medium for gathering information.    4.  DATA ANALYSIS.  Multivariate statisical procedures will        be used to test hypotheses.      Prior to each phase in the study, project advisors at Xeroxwould be consulted.  In addition, instruments for data collection would be carefully pretested.Products     A report will be presented to Xerox study advisors thatdescribes in full detail the study's findings and methodology.All technical data regarding system facilities and hardware willbe treated as proprietary, and the organization will not beidentified by name in any reports.  I would obtain companyapproval before publishing any results, with the exception ofmy dissertation.  This document will also treat system facilitiesand hardware information as proprietary and will not identifythe organization by name.Costs, Time Frame, and Next Steps     In return for the conduct of the proposed research, I askonly for coverage of the research expenses.  This would includematerials and supplies, system use, travel expenses if needed,etc.  No salary would be necessary.  My motivation for carryingout this research is to complete the requirements for mydoctoral dissertation at the Annenberg School of Communications.I believe that the proposed project would satisfy academicrequirements, be intellectually stimulating, and be useful foryour organization.  Furthermore, it would give me the opportunityto conduct research in an area which I find fascinating and drastically in need of empirical study.     The time frame for the proposed research is constrained onlyby my desire to finish my doctoral studies by June of 1982.In order to meet this deadline, work on a more detailedproposal should commence as soon as possible....Chip Steinfield------------------------------------------------------------*start*00404 00024 US Date: 16 Sept. 1981 8:53 am EDT (Wednesday)From: TELLEX.HenrSubject: Re: Add to @LaurelUsersIn-reply-to: Brotz.PA's message of 15 Sept. 1981 9:42 am PDT (Tuesday)To: Brotz.PAcc: TELLEX, LaurelSupport.PAMy disk was created by Gerry VerSchage. I just transferred into thisgroup and am new to the Alto world. I appreciate any help and am sorryfor any inconvenience.Greg.*start*00582 00024 US Date: 16 Sept. 1981 11:44 am PDT (Wednesday)From: Kolling.PASubject: disk fullTo: laurelsupportcc: kollingIt would be nice if when laurel says "disk full", it would abort the commandrather than demanding that the entire session be ended by "clicking red andblue".  It may be possible for the user to recover from disk full by deleting stufffrom the mail file.  Presently the message or file that was being saved when thedisk full occurs is lost forever...  I'd be happy to live with losing the undocommand at that point, if that's the problem...*start*00300 00024 US Date: 17 Sept. 1981 10:55 am EDT (Thursday)From: CONLEY.HenrSubject: Re: Add to @LaurelUsersIn-reply-to: Brotz.PA's message of 4 Sept. 1981 1:26 pm PDT (Friday)To: Brotz.PAcc: CONLEY, LaurelSupport.PAI