EL seems to do it.  On our mail system	I get a lot of "automated" reports from status perusing programs this way	I find it very comfortable.2.	We implemented a moderately useful facility called "Response Mail". This	logically looks a lot like me sending you a "form" for you to fill out and	return to me.  Perhaps there is some way of doing this that I haven't run	into yet.3.	Notes formatted like this one (indented paragraphs, hanging numbers to	the left) are not uncommon.  Some way of setting a left margin via a	Ruler or the like would be nice in the Laurel Editor, although again it 	may exist and I just don't know about it.Error Situations1.	I have encountered "Format error in mail file, get failed" after creating	(an undoubtedly illegal) mail file by "hand".  If there is a scavenger that	might have helped me, it would have been nice to have been told.*start*01495 00024 US Date: 28 Sept. 1981 1:58 pm PDT (Monday)From: Fikes.PASubject: Re: Outside people on internal distribution listsIn-reply-to: Schroeder's message of 25 Sept. 1981 3:40 pm PDT (Friday)To: Schroedercc: Brotz, Card, Birrell, Taft, Levin, Owners-CognitiveInterest^Reply-To: FikesAs the owner of CognitiveInterest^, I have encouraged the inclusion on thatdistribution list of non-Xerox people in the Palo Alto area who are interested inour Cognitive Science Discussion Group (CSDG) seminars.  That policy isconsistent with that of other AI groups in the area who run similar seminars(e.g., Stanford's SIGLUNCH series), and I think it helps to foster communicationand cooperation among the groups.  An example of the type of situation I thinkwe should strive to avoid occured a few years ago when Ed Feigenbaumexpressed his anger to me about Stanford not receiving notices of a talk that AlNewell had given at PARC.I also understand there are situations in which distribution to non-Xerox folks isinappropriate.  Therefore, I suggest that all non-Xerox people be removed fromCognitiveInterest^ and that a new dl be established, say calledCognitiveInterestAndFriends^, that is a superset of CognitiveInterest^ containingboth the internal and external folks.  (I will volunteer to help make thosechanges.)  The new list would then be used for announcement of open CSDG's. And for other uses, people could use whichever list suits their needs.richard   *start*00480 00024 US Date: 4 Nov. 1981 1:03 pm PST (Wednesday)From: Ritchie.PASubject: Laurel Manual SuggestionTo: BrotzDoug,As I mentioned, the manual is exceptionally well done.  I found onlyone nit; I annotated Figure 1 in the right margin indicating the upper menu,middle menu, lower menu, the three thumb bars, and the TOC, message display,and composition regions.  That could be done on Fig. 1 itself, and would havesaved me the uncertainty and trouble.Bob*start*00264 00024 US Date: 6 Nov. 1981 9:04 am PST (Friday)From: Schroeder.PASubject: Bug in LaurelTo: LaurelSupport.paLaurel should check the validity of the "Reply-To" name.  Perhaps this is anapplication for the single packet validity check function.*start*00879 00024 US From: deutsch.paDate: 17-Nov-81 10:00:32 PSTSubject: Requests for improvementsTo: LaurelSupportI have found a few very minor ways in which Laurel falls short ofperfection and would like you to consider them for some future release.1) Remote mail files!  I've been hearing promises for years, and I stillcan't read my mail from any machine except the one in my office(and have it work smoothly).2) Background mail acquisition.  I would like to be able to read mailas soon as it arrives, even if there is more mail to transfer.3) Ability to take material from Maintain or Chat transcripts and do anythinguseful with it.  When I select "New Form" it wipes out the lower window.4) Ability to create a second viewing or composition window.I still find Laurel one of the most wonderfully engineered systemsthis place has ever built.P. D