ard. If anyone else has any programs based on Play but not importing it directly,which you would like to run on Dolphins, you might want to make this changetoo.	Teri  *start*00269 00024 US Date: 7 Aug. 1981 4:59 pm PDT (Friday)From: Linda.PASubject: Publication ClearanceTo: Brotz,Andersoncc:  LindaThe publication, "Laurel Manual" has been cleared and approved with theappropriate signatures......it was filed today.Linda*start*00305 00024 US Date: 25 Aug. 1981 6:12 pm PDT (Tuesday)From: Taft.PASubject: DLS & ErnestineTo: Birrellcc: Transport.ms, TaftThe DLS now has a "Grapevine" command which is equivalent to "ConnectErnestine" but requiring just one keystroke.  (Sorry, the "E" command wasalready taken.)	Ed*start*00249 00024 US Date: 29 Sept. 1981 4:05 pm PDT (Tuesday)From: Kolling.PASubject: searchmailTo: laurelsupportcc: KollingWould you believe that if I feed searchmail a "malformed search string", itsearches the entire mail file anyway?*start*00914 00024 US Date: 6 Oct. 1981 5:20 pm PDT (Tuesday)From: Woods.PASubject: Laurel Error ReportTo: LaurelSupportLast week I sent in a few messages about a Laurel bug I'd run into, andincluded a pointer to the source of a private .bcd that was triggering the bug. Having found a way to get around the bug for a while, I intend to update the.bcd accordingly, and so I'm mailing you the relevant portion to keep with thebug report.The bug is that if Laurel is used to write a file (via Put or Copy or Move) andthen a Laurel-runnable bcd deletes the file via DestroyFile[NewFile["<file>",7]],and then another Put or Copy or Move attempts to write in that file, Laurelbombs out with signal 5205B (InvalidFP).  It appears that too much information isbeing cached, or perhaps Laurel should catch that signal and do a new directorysearch if the file no longer exists at the former disk address.*start*00219 00024 US Date: 7 Oct. 1981 10:13 am EDT (Wednesday)From: Lampson.PASubj