developmentdevelopement stop .  bellwhistle(This is the style in which you list all the substitutions that you wish toperform.  The laurel cherry character is typed as control-C; it is used to delimitthe patterns and replacements, since it is unlikely to be needed within them.)Then Run the InsertMail program; this will move the cherry stew into themiddle window, out of the way of the files that you will be bringing into thebottom window.For each file that you want to process, Get the file into the bottom window, Runthe program Substitute, and Put the file back (after checking that thesubstitutions performed as you expected).They will rarely perform as you expect.  For example, the substitutions abovewould transform a file consisting of the two sentences:	Developement of s and s proceeds apace.  Laurel soon to be morebaroque than Teco.into	developement of bells and whistles preceeds apace stop Laurel soon to bemore baroque than Teco.Note that the last period was not replaced, as it is at the end of the file and hasno spaces after it, and that the "D" has been demoted to a "d", probablyinadvertently.  Multiple global substitution schemes generally requiredebugging, which is convenient from within laurel, as the Forward commandwill move the substitution scheme back into the bottom window where it can beedited.The double quote character (") is reserved for quoting cherries or other doublequotes. A double quote is used instead of a single quote since single quotes areoften needed in the x's and y's, for example to get # or * or & to stand forthemselves in the pattern of the substitute command.  In summary:Let the contents of the middle window be	s0  x0  y0  s1  x1  y1   ...   xN  yN  sN+1where none of the x's or y's contains the cherry character or the doublequote character, and where none of the s's contains the cherry character.Then the effect of the program is the same as that of the following sequenceof Laurel substitute commands, performed in the order they are listed:Substitute x0 for y0Substitute x1 for y1...Substitute xN for yNThe s's are ignored; usually they are carriage returns or comments.If a double quote appears in one of the x's or y's, its only effect is to stripthe following character (presumably a cherry or double quote) of anyspecial lexical significance, so that the resulting x or y contains the following character and not the double quote.The s's must contain no cherries, not even quoted ones.If the contents of the middle window are not in the above form, or if oneof the x's or y's are longer than Laurel allows in its Substitute command, then an error message is given and the program exits to Laurel.This message itself is a valid substitution scheme (with unusually long s's); trymoving it into the middle window and applying it to the sentence above aboutlaurel and teco. ( = control G,  = control E).  The paragraph should betransformed as advertised.  In addition, the "No substitutions made" warningmessage will flash three times, because there are no occurences of "y0", "y1", or"yN" in the paragraph.The substitute command is now on [ivy]<GNelson>substitute.laurel.You might want to look over the mesa program there to see if I did anythingstupid.Greg*start*01191 00024 US Date: 7 Nov. 1981 2:54 pm PST (Saturday)From: Arndt.esSubject: Re: Kal.laurelTo: AllGames^cc: ArndtReply-To: ArndtSorry, I forgot to mention that the commands in Kal are Q (for quit; this requiresconfirmation, and once confirmed, Kal will ask you if you want to save theparameters) and ? (to list the command(s)).Austin Henderson found a bug in Kal, so I've stored a new version (version 2,dated 7 November 1981).When you type any non-command key, Kal expects you to change theparameters, so it lists the current parameters for you and then prompts you forthe new values.  The standard editing functions (backspace, backword, etc.) areall available.  If you enter an invalid number - or a text string longer than 10characters - Kal will output a "?" and start over with the same parameter.Key		Meaning		Initial SP	Use current value, go to next parameterInitial ESC	Display current valueInitial CR	Use current value for this parameter and exit parameter changingSP		Use the new value for this parameter and go to next parameterCR		Use the new value for this parameter and exit parameter changingDEL		Exit parameter changing~ Pete*start*00515 00024 US Date: 10 Nov. 1981 9:08 am PST (Tuesday)From: White.PASubject: Laurel Reply-To BugTo: LaurelSupportcc: WhiteIf I send a message via a private distribution list containing one or more Arpanetaddresses, Laurel supplies a Reply-To field in response to ESC, but the fieldcontains "White", rather than "White at PARC-MAXC".  When my Arpanetrecipients receive the message, they cannot use their mail system's REPLYcommand to respond because the reply-to address is not fully qualified.*start*00667 00024 US Date: 3 Dec. 1981 4:27 pm PST (Thursday)From: Deutsch.PASubject: Two very small Laurel suggestionsTo: LaurelSupport.PALaurel does a wonderful job of remembering things from one activation toanother.  One thing it doesn't currently remember is the last file name used for"Move to".  I imagine this would be a very small addition.On a slightly different topic, if I fire up Laurel with /s and then decide I wantto read my mail, it would be nice if I could select "Mail file" with the bluebutton and have it fill in the default mail file name Active (or even have it fillin Active, but not actually read it, when I fire up with /s).*start*00772 00024 US Date: 8 Dec. 1981 9:21 am PST (Tuesday)From: Artibee.PASubject: Re: Laurel 6 BugIn-reply-to: Brotz's message of 8 Dec. 1981 9:07 am PST (Tuesday)To: Brotzcc: ArtibeeI think there's a misunderstanding.Johnsson's message (probably composed/sent from a Pilot 8.0 