r five Ascii digits describing the length of the stamp. This is nearly always 00024.  Another Ascii space character is followed by threecharacter whose meanings are:1) U for undeleted, D for deleted (you should never see a D here).2) S for seen, U for unseen.  The ? displayed in the mark field of the table ofcontents means this character = U.3) The mark character (other than ?) for this message.  In the example above themark character happens to be a blank.A carriage return completes the 24 characters of the standard stamp.The text of the message follows immediately, and the next stamp beginsimmediately after that message.  There are no padding bytes added anywhere;stamps and messages may begin or end on odd numbered bytes.The last character of the last message is the last character in the mail file.The format of the table of contents file is considerably more complicated.  Isuggest you not deal with them.-- Doug*start*01164 00024 US Date: 26 Jan. 1982 4:53 pm PST (Tuesday)From: Birrell.paSubject: Re: "fixing" mail headersTo: Baskett, McGregorcc: BrotzTrue, the answer command could recover a bit better (although, of course, itwould be nicer if people didn't send illegal headers).  I expect Doug will add itto his wish-list.---------------------------Date: 26 Jan. 1982 4:29 pm PST (Tuesday)From: Baskett.PASubject: Re: "fixing" mail headersIn-reply-to: Birrell's message of 26 Jan 1982 14:33 PSTTo: Birrellcc: McGregorThanks.  That all makes sense.  So how about an error message that says "Can't'cc' to a) someone in the original to list or b) someone in the original cc list. Type ESC to forge ahead anyway."?  That way it would do as much of the workas it could for me and I would just have to patch up what it couldn't handle.  Infact, (now that I am thinking of possible work for other people to do!) it couldinclude the unparseable strings in field marks ( and its cousin) in the cc lineof the answer form.  That would make it even