gestion to add to your probably-never-to-be-implemented wish list:If an incoming message says "Reply-to: distributionList^", then Answer shouldconstruct a form that likewise says "Reply-to: distributionList^".  That way,someone can start a discussion with the express intent of having all replies (andreplies to replies, etc.) be distributed to all members of the group.  Currentlywhat happens is that everyone has to remember to type "A" to confirm delivery;sometimes people forget, with the result that some members of the group do notreceive all the messages.	Ed*start*00914 00024 US Date: 12 May 1982 5:21 pm PDT (Wednesday)From: Taft.PASubject: Retrieval to wrong mail fileTo: LaurelSupportI sometimes "lose" messages as a result of doing a NewMail when the mail file issomething other than Active without realizing I have done so.  That is, I switchto some other mail file in order to look at old messages, and forget to switch backto Active before retrieving new mail.  If I don't immediately deal with all thenewly-arrived messages, they remain in the other mail file instead of Active,and I lose track of them until I next happen to look at that mail file.Perhaps Laurel should post a warning in the feedback window if NewMail isdone when the mail file is other than Active.  (This need not demand anyadditional confirmation, since the user can easily move the received messages tothe correct mail file if he is made aware that this has happened.)	Ed*start*00847 00024 US Date: 14 May 1982 3:43 pm PDT (Friday)From: Taft.PASubject: Needless dirtying of mail filesTo: LaurelSupport"Mail file" opens the mail file for writing, which changes the file's creation date,even if the contents of the file are never actually changed.  This causes needlessextra backup traffic when mail files are backed up on file servers by automaticmeans (Store/ua, Backup, or SModel).Laurel should either open a mail file read-only until the first attempted write(then close and re-open it for writing), or else should save the old creation dateand put it back when the file is closed if the file was never actually written on. (The Alto OS uses the latter strategy, and it has served well in coping withclient programs that are insufficiently specific about their intentions when theyopen files.)	Ed*start*01203 00024 US Date: 23 July 1982 2:55 pm EDT (Friday)From: Hube.WBSTSubject: Comment on LaurelTo: LaurelImp^.pacc: HubeReply-To: HubeI've been an Alto user for some time now and I would like to say that Laurel isin my opinion the most well designed software user-interface I've seen ( andthat includes Star software and Mesa software too).  However, so as not to giveyou too swelled a head, I would like to make a suggestion for improvement (assuming you may someday issue another revision).Always display the ' TO: ' field for all mail. This would allow a user to determine if a message is directed at him/her directly( indicating importance or need for response ) or whether it is directed to a DL (indicating potentially less importance ) or whether he is only copied (i.e. cc:) to. It sure would help weed out the garbage from the interesting stuff.  If screenspace is a limitation, it would be satisfactory to just indicate by a single lettercode whether the user is: a) directly addressed (by user-id) b) indirectly addressed (by DL) c) or merely copiedAn example of this would be D, I, or C respectively. Thankyou in advance for your consideration.Randy*start*00671 00024 US Date: 29 April 1982 1:41 pm PDT (Thursday)From: Ciccarelli.PASubject: A useful Laurel form...To: Brotzcc: CiccarelliDoug,I often use InsertMail to place messages to myself into my Active.mail file.  I gottired of having to remember how to do this without getting a "bad date???" orbad Sender field, so I made a simple form called Reminder.form to retrieve via"Get".Since you're the Laurel "Kahuna", I thought I'd zip off a 