an)	Xail10.al  for people who like the fixed-pitch Sail10.al, aka Gacha.Both of these have some of the SAIL special characters in the standard places:	infinity, partial, subset, superset, intersection, union, alignmentTab,	exchangeArrow, and forwardArrow;but no others (no room).  They also have distinct bitmaps for left and rightsingle quote, unlike Laurel10.al.  They have a down arrow, but it has beenmoved from its Sail home at ^A to the ^D slot instead, since ^A is hard to typein Laurel.Because of the different down arrow and the lack of the relational operators like"less than or equal to", you might want to \input a file like my ownLaurelEditing.tex at the start of your TEX file:\chcode'4_8  %make ^D also a subscript character\def\le{\mathrel\char'424 }  %ways to type the arithmetic relationals\def\ge{\mathrel\char'425 }\def\ne{\mathrel\char'434 }\def\lt{\mathrel\char'074 }  %just for symmetry\def\gt{\mathrel\char'076 }This stuff is on [Ivy]<Ramshaw>Laurel>  (or /Ivy/Ramshaw/Laurel/ dependingupon your religion):	SmashFont.Laurel	Laurel10.al	Sorrel10.al	Xail10.al	LaurelEditing.tex.I am willing to give short Prepress lessons to people who want to produce stillother fonts to use with Laurel via SmashFont,Lyle	*start*02181 00024 US Date: 20 Sept. 1982 10:27 am PDT (Monday)From: Brotz.PASubject: Re: Laurel ProgramsIn-reply-to: Gloger.es's message of 19 Sept. 1982 10:40 pm PDT (Sunday)To: Gloger.escc: Brotz, Neumeister.esConsider the following to be the document that describes how to write Laurelrunnable programs.Laurel will run Alto-Mesa programs that use IODefs for input and output andthat use any interfaces exported by the Mesa Nucleus.  PupDefs and FTPDefs arealso available, as are several Laurel internal interfaces, although the Laurelinterfaces are not documented.  Only the User half of FTPDefs is implemented,and only the Send half of EFTPDefs is implemented.Simple programs using only IODefs for interaction are easy to write and shouldrun in the same way both under Mesa.image and under Laurel.  Your program isstarted when the Run command is invoked, running your startup code.  Tofinish, just run off the end of the main line code in your startup module.  Donot call ImageDefs.StopMesa for obvious reasons, and do not add or deletecleanuip procedures.  If you use PupDefs, be sure not to turn the Pup Packageon or off (it's already on.)  Use Storage for allocating and freeing storage.  Laurelwill check your allocation, and will crash spectacularly if any allocated storageis not freed by the time your program finishes.The complete list of exports from Laurel is listed below.Laurel: CONFIGURATION  EXPORTS  -- from Mesa  AllocDefs, BcdOps, DirectoryDefs, DiskKDDefs, FrameDefs, FrameOps, FSPDefs,  ImageDefs, KeyDefs, MiscDefs, Process, ProcessDefs, Runtime, SegmentDefs,Storage,  StreamDefs, StreamScan, String, StringDefs, SystemDefs, Time, TimeDefs,  TrapDefs,   -- from Pup  BufferDefs, ByteBltDefs, CommUtilDefs, DriverDefs, EFTPDefs, PupDefs,  PupPktDefs, PupRouterDefs, PupStream, Stream,   -- from FTP  FTPDefs, TimeExtraDefs,   -- from Grapevine  LocateDefs, NameInfoDefs, NameInfoSpecialDefs, ProtocolDefs,  RetrieveDefs, SendDefs,   -- from Laurel  crD, csD, displayCommon, DMSTimeDefs, dsD, Editor, exD, inD, intCommon,  IODefs, LaurelExecDefs, lmD, MailParse, mfD, opD, prD, Sequin, tfD, tsD,vmD -- Doug*start*08962 00024 US Date: Wed, 9 Mar 83 17:50 PSTFrom: Brotz.PASubject: Laurel 6.1 changesTo: Schroeder, JWhite, Taft, Levincc: BrotzThis message contains all information about Laurel 6.1 that you will need to keepthe Laurel world going in my absence.USER PERCEIVABLE CHANGESLaurel 6.1's run file is 77 pages bigger than Laurel 6's.  This is mainly due tothe inclusion of VM, the ChollaCmd module, the ReplaceMailOp module, andgeneral ignoring of bit-bumming.Blue button New mail:  When invoked with the blue mouse button, Laurel willretrieve new mail one message at a time, checkpointing the mail file locally anddeleting the message on the server, until all mail is received or the local diskfills up.  A warning message appears if this New mail mode is invoked, requiringthe user to confirm that this slower than normal mail retrieval is actuallywanted.Arpa header standard:  Laurel 6.1 contains an RFC822-only header parser. Certain addresses acceptable in the past are no longer acceptable.  This will showup as the Answer command being unable to generate an answer form for thesenow illegal headers.  Laurel 6.1 will no longer append an Arpa host on outgoingmessages.  The Answer command may also be confused by legal headersproduced in the past that depended on Arpa host minimization algorithms, i.e.,the header    From: Brotz@PARC-MAXC    To: Foowill be answered as    cc: Foo.Arpasince the new parser understands that the sender was in the Arpa registry, andtherefore Foo must have been shorthand for Foo.Arpa.    Such cases should be rare.    The profile entry ArpaGatewayHostNames is no longer supported.CR insertion in Deliver:  Laurel 6.1 no longer automatically folds headers andplaces CR's in outgoing messages.  A new profile entry, DeliverWithCRs, isallowed, and is defaulted to FALSE.  If TRUE, Laurel 6.1 will insert CR's as inLaurel 6.  I would not advertise this feature.Display of long lines in the displayed message window:  This will go muchfaster in Laurel 6.1.  Pseudo-CR's are written into the mail file to achieve thisspeed-up.Remote file names:  In the profile entry RemoteFilePath, a $ character is replacedby the current user's name (without registry) when computing the remote filename.  This is only of interest to remote mail file users who share a commonLaurel.profile.New date syntax on outgoing messages:  The new format is  Wed, 9 Mar 83 16:32 PST   (Yeccchhhh).  This applies to the COM-T command as well.  The date at theupper right of the screen remains as old.INTERNAL CHANGESVM has replaced the Core for all File I/O.  The new interface Core, is a thinveneer over VM, and is similar to the now defunct CoreDefs.  One new module,CoreImpl, papers over this interface, providing the same old file name cache,which is now used only for enumerating recently accessed files in the bracketsfill-in code.The VirtualMgr now retains only a single page sized buffer for each object(displayed message, toc, and composed message).  TOC operations now requirelocks to operate properly in Cholla's multiprocessing environment.  SeeVirtualMgrDefs for details.  In essence, you must call LockTOC[tocHandle] toobtain a key (a CARDINAL) which must be passed to all other TOC manipulationprocedures.  Most often, a call to WaitForLock[tocHandle] is more appropriatethan a direct call to LockTOC, which may return 0, indicating that the tocHandlewas already locked.  When finished manipulating a toc, you should callUnlockTOC[tocHandle, key].Most operations level modules have been recoded to use CoreStreams rather thantheir own streaming procedures.A new interface, ccD: ChollaCmdDefs, glues together the Cholla part of Laurel. One procedure from this interface is used throughout Laurel proper; it isGetTOCForFile[fileName, tocClass], which returns a locked tocHandle with itskey.  This procedure manages a complicated toc cache for Cholla.  Laurel properwill use only "laurel" as the tocClass.  Passing a NIL filename to this procedureclears out that classes cache (see the Quit command for details.)  If this proceduregives you any trouble, see Will Crowther.ReplaceMailOp is very complicated.  It embodies most of the InsertMail code, butallows general insertion, deletion, or replacement of a single message in a mailfile, with corresponding changes in the TOC.  It is not actually used in Laurelproper, but is called from Insert.laurel.  Cholla uses it all over the place.The old module named ExpandOp is now named FileOp.  Expand in this moduleno longer understands @filename syntax.The new mail parser's interface is MailParseDefs (not MailParse), and itsimplementation is in the new module ArpaMailParser.  There are no longer anyBackup procedures supplied to this module's procedures.  The parser maintains aone character cache for those cases where it needs to look ahead one character. It will read the first character of the next header field or the CR of the linefollowing the last header field after reading a field body in GetFieldBody orParseNameList.  This is important when counting calls to the ReadChar procedureto locate field body boundaries in IntHardcopyCom and elsewhere.  The generalrule to follow is that everything works fine as long as you are streamingthrough the header, from field name to field body to field name to field body,etc.  If you must reset the ReadChar routine, you must FinalizeParse andInitializeParse to reset the cache correctly.  There is no performance penalty fordoing this, as the new parser does almost nothing during those calls.IF YOU WANT TO BUILD A NEW CHOLLA AND LAURELCommand files and file lists abound on the [Cherry]<Cholla>1Txx> directories. Source.Laurel, Source.LaurelDefs, Object.Laurel, and Object.LaurelDefs are filelists only--DO NOT USE THEM FOR COMPILATION.  Compile.LaurelDefs andCompile.Laurel are file lists containing the correct compilation order and leavingout those modules that should not be recompiled (e.g., LaurelExecDefs, whichMaintain and Chat depend on.)  To compile all of the Cholla impl's (andtherefore all of the Laurel impl's) say  Compile @Compile.laurel@to the executive.To bind and build an image using bootmesa, use the command files mc.cm andml.cm (for Make Cholla and Make Laurel).  Each one is to be invoked by saying  Bind @mcor  Bind @mlto the executive,The Laurel configuration is a subset of the Cholla configuration.  Laurel leavesmany Cholla interfaces unbound.  These procedures can never be called fromLaurel, so this is ok, but binding Laurel normally produces Binder warningmessages.  The ml.cm file ignores these warnings; the mc.cm file does not.  Thecorrect procedure when binding new versions is to bind a Cholla first, and if itsucceeds, then bind a Laurel.  The Cholla bind will detect any problems; if thereare none, then the Laurel binding warning may be ignored safely.Cholla will behave exactly as Laurel (displaying a Laurel herald, and no BBoardcommand) if the profile does not contain Cholla: TRUE.  Laurel will neverbehave as Cholla (it checks if certain Cholla procedures are bound).  The versionstring prefix is set up in InitInteractor, its suffix is set in Overview.  The currentprefixes are "Laurel 6.1" and "Cholla 1".  The current suffix is "T34".  Beforereleasing, the suffix in Overview should be set to "".USEFUL FILES TO HAVE AROUND IF YOU ARE GOING TO WORK ONLAURELAll of the files on [Cherry]<Cholla>1Txx> where xx is the latest version.  This isthe dumping ground for Laurel's pieces.  Other necessary files are:[Ivy]<Mesa>  Binder.bcd!2  Compiler.image!3  Fetch.bcd!1  Front.run!1  Lister.bcd!1  Mesa.image!1  MesaFont.Strike!1  RunMesa.run!1  XDebug.image!1[Ivy]<Mesa>Bootmesa>  Boot.bcd!1[Ivy]<Mesa>FTP>  FTPDefs.bcd!1  FTPForLaurel.bcd!1  TimeExtraDefs.bcd!1  TimeExtraDefs.mesa!1  TimeExtras.bcd!1[Ivy<Mesa>Pup>  BufferDefs.bcd!1  ByteBltDefs.bcd!1  ByteBltDefs.mesa!1  CommUtilDefs.bcd!1  DriverDefs.bcd!1  EFTPDefs.bcd!1  EFTPSend.bcd!1  PupDefs.bcd!1  PupPktDefs.bcd!1  PupRouterDefs.bcd!1  PupStream.bcd!1  PupTypes.bcd!1  Stream.bcd!1  TinyPup.bcd!1[Ivy]<Mesa>System>  AllocDefs.bcd!1  BcdOps.bcd!1  DirectoryDefs.bcd!1  DiskKDDefs.bcd!1  FrameDefs.bcd!1  FrameOps.bcd!1  FSPDefs.bcd!1  ImageDefs.bcd!1  KeyDefs.bcd!1  LoaderOps.bcd!1  MiscDefs.bcd!1  Process.bcd!1  ProcessDefs.bcd!1  Runtime.bcd!1  SegmentDefs.bcd!1  Storage.bcd!1  StreamDefs.bcd!1  StreamScan.bcd!1  String.bcd!1  StringDefs.bcd!1  SystemDefs.bcd!1  Time.bcd!1  TimeDefs.bcd!1  TrapDefs.bcd!1[Ivy]<Mesa>TableCompiler>  TableCompiler.bcd!1[Indigo]<Grapevine>  GrapevineUser.bcd  LocateDefs.bcd  NameInfoDefs.bcd  NameInfoSpecialDefs.bcd  ProtocolDefs.bcd  RetrieveDefs.bcd  SendDefs.bcd[Indigo]<Grapevine>VM>  AltoFile.bcd  FileDefs.bcd  Sequin.bcd  VMDefs.bcd  VMSpecial.bcd  VMStorage.bcd*start*02070 00024 US Date: Mon, 14 Mar 83 14:37 PSTFrom: Brotz.PASubject: Laurel runnable bcd'sTo: Schroeder, Levin, Taft, JWhite, McCreight, Willie-SueFor Laurel 6.1, the interface LaurelExecDefs has not been recompiled from thatused in Laurel 6, therefore, all programs that depend on that interface plus Mesasystem interfaces only will run unchanged in Laurel 6.1.  This includesMaintain.laurel and Chat.laurel.MailFileScavenger.laurel depends on the Core interface, therefore, you will needthe new one.All of the runnable programs are stored on [Cherry]<Cholla>Laurel>, withversion numbers that correspond to the temporary version of Laurel 6.1 storedthere.  The sources for these programs are on [Cherry]<Cholla>1T35> (the 1T35being the current temporary version of Laurel and Cholla).Basic is stored on [Cherry]<Cholla>Basic>.  There is a 1T35 compatible Basic.laurelon [Cherry]<Cholla>Laurel>.  Basic has never received much use, and there aredefinitely some problems with it.  However, if you wish to continue to supportBasic, it should be reasonably simple to figure out what is going on by readingthe files stored on [Cherry]<Cholla>Basic>.The remaining runnable programs are pretty much the same ones that wereoffered for Laurel 6.  InsertMail.laurel is now called Insert.laurel.  There is also aReplace.laurel that behaves like Insert.laurel, except that it replaces the messageselected in the TOC.  Delete.laurel does an immediate delete of the messageselected in the TOC; it is not very useful for the general public and probablyshould not be announced.SearchMail.laurel works as before.  A new program, Extract.laurel behaves likeSearchMail, except that it copies the matching text into the composed message. With an imaginative search specification, this program can generate amazingreports and summaries.I declare that this message ties up the remaining loose ends.  John White willhave a copy of my Laurel partition, so anything that I have dropped on the floorshould be found there as a last resort.-- Doug*start*00992 00024 US Date: Mon, 14 Mar 83 16:51 PSTFrom: Brotz.PASubject: FarewellTo: AllDc^.dc, AllDlos^.dlos, AllEs^.es, AllHenr^.henr, AllLb^.lb, AllPa^.pa,AllRx^.rx, AllSthq^.sthq, AllWbst^.wbst, AllEos^.eosReply-To: Brotz%Shasta@SU-ScoreHaving served you the past six years as a contributor to Laurel and as part ofLaurelSupport.pa, I feel as if the distribution of this message is to my close circleof friends.Today is my last day at Xerox; tomorrow I will be a member of Adobe Systems.The next version of Laurel will be released within the next few months.  I hopeyou will find it to be satisfactory.  Remember, please address your gripes, praise,error reports and dreams to LaurelSupport.pa, which is being left in capablehands.If you wish to get in touch with me, my new addresses are:Postal:Doug BrotzAdobe Systems, Inc.2685 Marine WayMountain View, CA 94043Telephone:(415) 969-5251Net:Brotz%Shasta@SU-ScoreI wish you all the very best.-- Doug*start*01137 00024 US Date: Wed, 6 Apr 83 15:15 PSTFrom: Taft.PASubject: Laurel development diskTo: JWhitecc: Schroeder, TaftWe need to make some minor changes to Laurel in order to prepare it for release. There are some problems that arise when running on a 64K Alto: the Runcommand doesn't work at all due to running out of memory, and performance isgenerally poor.  We hope we can fix this by some tuning of various parameters(size of initial frame heap, free storage heap, and VM buffer storage).  We mayalso experiment with some packaging changes; e.g., reduce the number ofinterfaces exported from the top-level configuration to the minimum required, inorder to minimize the size of the LoadState.Assuming the non-Cholla part of Laurel is in a stable state, I would like to getcopies of all the files.  Doug led me to understand that you are keeping a Laureldevelopment disk (or disk image stored on Cherry).  I believe the best way for usto get started would be to copy this disk.Would you please copy the Laurel development disk to Cherry (if it's not therealready) and tell me where it is?  Thanks.	Ed*start*00816 00024 US Date: 7 April 1983 9:50 am PST (Thursday)From: JWhite.PASubject: Re: Laurel development diskIn-reply-to: Taft's message of Wed, 6 Apr 83 15:15 PSTTo: Taftcc: JWhite, SchroederEd,All of the current Laurel (and Cholla) source files and bcd files are stored on 			[cherry]<cholla>1T35>Also, there is an image of Doug's Laurel/Cholla partition stored on			[cherry]<jwhite>Brotz>bfs4Nothing has changed since Doug left; although I'm about to make a minorchange to Cholla.  I would like to keep Laurel and Cholla internal releasessynchronized.  So, I want to try and have Cholla run on top of any changesmade to Laurel.  Doug always viewed Laurel 6.1 as a subset of Cholla and thuskept the "truth" copy of everything in a single subdirectory.  Can we continuethis?-- John *start*00961 00024 US Date: Thu, 7 Apr 83 17:41 PSTFrom: Taft.PASubject: Re: Laurel development diskIn-reply-to: "JWhite's message of 7 April 1983 9:50 am PST (Thursday)"To: JWhitecc: Taft, SchroederI have copied the disk image, and Mike, Roy, and I did some experiments. We've concluded that something more than simple tuning is required.  We areinvestigating alternatives ranging from buggering the Loader so that less has tobe swapped in all at once during the Run command, to changing Run so that ona 64K Alto it doesn't work in the normal way but instead invokes any of a fewprograms that have been bound into Laurel (probably just Maintain and Chat).In any event, we will take care to ensure t