ace compression.  It is done in a fairly simpleminded way, but theread-ahead and write-behind provided by the Mesa VM package is supposed totake care of making bulk transfers of this sort efficient.  However, the VMmechanisms are subverted if there isn't enough memory, as is true on a 64Kmachine.2) The Laurel 6.1 editor has a bigger working set than the one in Laurel 6. When you hear the disk seeking a lot during editing, I believe it is due to codethrashing.I have received several reports of Laurel 6.1 "freezing" for varying lengths oftime.  Yours is the first from anyone not on net 3.  I have been assuming untilnow that the freezes are caused by some sort of bad Ethernet traffic on net 3(e.g., uncontrolled broadcasts).  I have not yet been able to gather sufficientevidence of this, however.	Ed*start*00507 00024 US Date: Tue, 5 Jul 83 17:48 PDTFrom: Taft.PASubject: Error in Answer formTo: LaurelSupportIf there is ever a Laurel 6.2, the following should be fixed.  "Answer", whenapplied to a message with a From field such as:From: "jjs@mit-cipg"@mit-mc.ARPAproduces a header with an In-reply-to field of:In-reply-to: ""jjs@mit-cipg"@mit-mc.ARPA's message of 15 Jun 83 10:11:31 EDT"The embedded double-quote characters needed to be prefixed with "\" in order toconform to RFC 822.*start*01090 00024 US From: deutsch.paDate:  5-Jul-83 23:09:32 PDTSubject: Re: Laurel 6.1 performance problemsIn-reply-to: Taft's message of Tue, 5 Jul 83 14:19 PDTTo: Taftcc: LaurelSupportI ran the What program on my machine when Laurel 6.1 was firstreleased and sent you the results, which didn't correspond to either ofthe example results in the release message.  You said I had the rightPROMs and didn't have to do anything.While I would have to do some experimenting to verify this, Laurel 6.1seems to take much, much longer to delete messages early in message fileswhen quitting, and in particular, the disk sounds areclearly made by seeking back and forth a