TFrom: Taft.PASubject: Header checkingTo: LaurelSupportA message with a bad header was sent recently to a rather wide audience;attempting to Hardcopy this message caused Laurels to die left and right.  Ibelieve all the error reports were for Laurel 6, so perhaps Laurel 6.1 does nothave this problem.However, the bad message was sent by a Laurel 6.1 user.  The problem with theheader was that the extra CR at the end was missing.  The first several lines ofthe body happened to begin with spaces and/or tabs, so they appeared to becontinuations of the last line of the header, which was a Reply-to field.This made the Reply-to field syntactically incorrect.  The header parser knows itis incorrect, since attempting to answer it yields a syntax error.  However, forsome reason Laurel failed to detect this during Deliver; and thus it permitted thisbad header to escape.I suspect the header parser is being called by Deliver only to extract theinformation required for delivery (To and cc); and since the Reply-to field isn'trequired for delivery, it isn't getting parsed.  This is incorrect.  Deliver shouldparse every field, even if it uses only some of the information.*start*01026 00024 US Date: Thu, 14 Jul 83 17:49 PDTFrom: Freige.PASubject: Error ReportTo: LaurelSupport.PAI had just composed a "new form" message to Bob Ritchie, invoked "Deliver" andwas then prompted to send this message.  Nothing unusual, except a few minutesbefore working on the Ritchie message, part of the displayed message in thecenter section of my screen got fuzzy and became unreadable.Nancy Freige, x-4801Laurel 6.1  Alto I (064#134#) with Ram only MDS: 00 Banks: 100000 code:000051Signal 002661 in Faultsmsg 165520, msg^ 173774 001024 165400 000202BackStop, 003405Signaller, 000521Faults, 000516Swapper, 002050Modules, 002223Modules, 002160Modules, 000554Modules, 001737PupSockets, 000277PupPktCool, 004522PupPktCool, 000517PupByteStreams[352B], 000346Protocol, 000650Sen