g-83  9:13:39 EDT"To: shinbrot.wbstcc: EthernetInterest^.dlos, LaurelSupport.PAReply-To: LaurelSupport.PAFirst of all, EthernetInterest^.dlos was not the right list to send your question to. That list is for messages having to do with the Ethernet hardware, protocols, andproducts; whereas you are asking a question about mail systems.Second, when you have basic procedural questions such as this, I suggest youconsult some experienced local user for advice rather than broadcasting questionsto a distribution list.  If you don't know whom to start with, I would suggest theperson who registered you as a Laurel user.To briefly answer your specific questions:  a) You get on the list.  b) There is no automatic compilation or archiving of messages to interestgroups; and there is no analog to the "bulletin board" facilities available in somesystems.  However, for some groups, people have collected the messages andstored them in a public place.  I would suggest asking the owner of the groupsin question, who can be reached by sending a message to Owner-X where X isthe name of the group.  c) Xerox users are not ordinarily permitted to "get onto" the Arpanet in thesense of being able to initiate terminal connections or transfer files to and fromother Arpanet sites.  Only people engaged in activities sponsored by ARPA orother government agencies are supposed to have such access.  However, you cancorrespond with Arpanet users (and other people reachable via the ARPAInternet) by electronic mail, so long as you are careful not to carry on Xeroxbusiness or to send messages that could be construed as promoting a Xeroxproduct.  There is information about corresponding with Arpanet users in theLaurel manual, and more information in the Laurel tutorial mail files(Tutorial.mail and Laurel61.mail).	Ed Taft (for LaurelSupport)*start*00652 00024 US Date: Thu, 1 Sep 83 16:25 EDTFrom: Hengst.WBSTSubject: Error ReportTo: LaurelSupport.PAMoving window boundaries back to the